      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The initial step of iRT regression is to estimate the empirical RTs of a peptide set with known iRT scores... In the simplest case, this is achieved by computing an extracted ion chromatogram (XIC) for iRT peptide precursors... we extract the RTs at the maximum of the intensity traces stored in the rawrr Chromatogram object and fit a linear model of the form rt = a + b \u00b7 score.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms extraction of RTs from XICs of iRT calibrants and fitting linear models. However, the paper does not use the specific variable name 'rtFittedAPEX' or specify exactly 11 iRT peptides; the example uses iRT peptides but the exact count and variable naming are not specified in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "linear-regression-fitting-for-chromatography",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have extracted retention times at peak maxima (rtFittedAPEX) from extracted-ion chromatograms (XICs) of known internal RT calibrants (e.g., 11 iRT peptides with annotated iRTscore values)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
