      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-metadata-interpretation/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Centroided data also makes it possible to graph spectra using signal-to-noise as response value... The horizontal blue line indicates a signal-to-noise ratio of 5.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates signal-to-noise extraction and visualization for quality assessment.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-metadata-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when troubleshooting spectral quality issues by examining per-scan metadata such as signal-to-noise ratios, baseline noise floors, or acquisition time budgets",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:38:54.634539+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-metadata-interpretation/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "However, analyzing Orbitrap data in R has so far only been possible after raw data conversion to exchange formats like mz(X)ML... Unfortunately, conversion is accompanied by a loss of Orbitrap-specific information... Libraries that support working with the spectral data in R also exist, for instance, the Bioconductor package MSnbase. However, they require conversion of raw data to exchange formats like mzML, which is primarily supported by the ProteoWizard project and its software tool MSconvert.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly contrasts rawrr (direct .raw access) with ProteoWizard/MSconvert (conversion to mzML) and notes loss of Orbitrap-specific information in conversion.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-metadata-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: Input is not a Thermo Fisher .raw file (e.g., mzML, mzXML, or other vendor formats) \u2014 use vendor-neutral tools like ProteoWizard or pyteomics instead.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:38:54.634539+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-metadata-interpretation/010",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In the academic environment, Max Quant and Skyline are by far the most popular ones. These software tools usually offer GUIs that control running predefined analysis templates/workflows... Naturally, these offer greater analytical flexibility but require programming skills from the end-user... We strongly believe that a library providing raw data reading would finally close the gap and facilitate modular end-to-end analysis pipeline development in R.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly contrasts GUI-based tools (MaxQuant, Skyline) with programmatic R library approach for modular pipeline development.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-metadata-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Particularly useful when integrating raw data into modular R-based pipelines where GUI tools like MaxQuant or Skyline would constrain analytical flexibility.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:38:54.634539+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "By using the read Index() function a data.frame that indexes all scans found in a raw fi le is returned. When subsetting it for our scan type of interest it becomes clear that the example data was recorded using parallel reaction monitoring (PRM) since the parent ion 487.2567 was isolated in regularly spaced intervals for fragment ion recording. The delta between consecutive scans is always 22 scans (one PRM cycle)",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly demonstrates extracting scan indices and validating inter-scan deltas for PRM consistency.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Verify that parallel reaction monitoring (PRM) or targeted MS/MS acquisition maintains consistent scan spacing across all monitoring cycles by extracting scan indices from raw Orbitrap files and validating inter-scan deltas.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:39:18.053574+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our novel package rawrr now provides complete, OS-independent access to all spectral data logged in Thermo Fisher Scientific raw files... By using the read Index() function a data.frame that indexes all scans found in a raw fi le is returned.",
      "asbval:note": "rawrr is confirmed as the R package providing readIndex() for scan metadata extraction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "rawrr \u2014 R package that wraps RawFileReader .NET assembly; provides readIndex() function to extract scan metadata and scanType information from .raw files",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:39:18.053574+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "rawrr utilizes a vendor-provided API named Raw File Reader to access spectral data logged in proprietary Thermo Fisher Scientific raw files... Calling a wrapper method typically results in the execution of methods defined in the Raw File Reader dynamic link library provided by Thermo Fisher Scientific.",
      "asbval:note": "RawFileReader is confirmed as the underlying vendor API/assembly used by rawrr for binary file parsing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "RawFileReader \u2014 .NET assembly (C#) underlying rawrr; implements low-level binary file parsing and data extraction from Thermo Fisher Orbitrap .raw files",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:39:18.053574+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our R package rawDiag (J. Proteome Res. 2018, 17 (8), 2908\u20132914) has provided the proof-of-principle how access to mass spectrometry raw files can be realized by wrapping a vendor-provided advanced programming interface (API) for the purpose of metadata analysis and visualization.",
      "asbval:note": "rawDiag is mentioned as providing metadata analysis and visualization for raw files, but the paper does not explicitly demonstrate its use for detecting acquisition irregularities or scan-level cycle verification. The card's claim about detecting acquisition irregularities is not directly supported in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "rawDiag \u2014 R package for LC-MS method optimization and quality control; can visualize scan-level metrics and detect acquisition irregularities",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:39:18.053574+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "This use case shows how easy it is to work directly with raw-formated Orbitrap data after installing our R package rawrr which applies vendor APIs for data access. We use a complete LC-MS run recorded on a Q Exactive HF Orbitrap by parallel reaction monitoring (PRM)... The delta between consecutive scans is always 22 scans (one PRM cycle)",
      "asbval:note": "The paper demonstrates exactly this use case with Orbitrap .raw files and PRM cycle validation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have a Thermo Fisher Scientific Orbitrap .raw file and need to confirm that a targeted acquisition method (e.g., PRM targeting a specific precursor m/z) is achieving uniform cycle timing.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:39:18.053574+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "By using the read Index() function a data.frame that indexes all scans found in a raw fi le is returned... The delta between consecutive scans is always 22 scans (one PRM cycle) and the dependency Type of the MS2 scans is NA (since it was triggered by an inclusion list).",
      "asbval:note": "readIndex() returns a data.frame with scan indices and type information; inter-scan deltas are computed from this data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-method-cycle-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Data frame with scan indices, scan types, and inter-scan delta values for validation of PRM cycle consistency",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:39:18.053574+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-precursor-identification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The code chunk below demonstrates how the function read Chromatogram() is called on the R command line to return a rawrr Chromatogram Set object of the type xic. This object is plotted for visual inspection (see Figure 4 for resulting plot)... Each XIC was calculated using a tolerance of 10 ppm around the target mass and using only MS1-level scans.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly demonstrates XIC extraction with tight mass tolerance (10 ppm) for iRT peptide precursors from Orbitrap raw files.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-precursor-identification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Identify and extract precursor m/z values and retention times for peptide standards from Thermo Orbitrap raw files using extracted ion chromatograms (XIC) with tight mass tolerance.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:39:30.615372+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-precursor-identification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "By applying linear regression, one can convert observed peptide retention times (RTs) into dimensionless scores termed iRT values and vice versa. This can be used for retention time calibration/prediction. In addition, fitted iRT regression models provide highly valuable information about LC-MS run performance.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates iRT regression workflow comparing observed RTs against known iRT reference scores.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-precursor-identification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "comparison of experimental retention times against known reference standards",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
