    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/raw-file-data-extraction-via-api/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our R package rawDiag (J. Proteome Res. 2018, 17 (8), 2908\u20132914) has provided the proof-of-principle how access to mass spectrometry raw files can be realized by wrapping a vendor-provided advanced programming interface (API) for the purpose of metadata analysis and visualization.",
      "asbval:note": "rawDiag is mentioned as a predecessor package for metadata analysis and visualization, but the paper does not explicitly state that rawDiag 'uses rawrr' or that rawrr evolved from rawDiag in a dependency sense. The paper states rawrr's 'codebase evolved from our previous R package rawDiag' (passage 3), indicating rawDiag is a predecessor, not a dependent tool. The claim of rawDiag using rawrr is not supported; the relationship is reversed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "raw-file-data-extraction-via-api",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "rawDiag: R package for LC-MS method optimization and quality control; uses rawrr for fast multiplatform reading and ggplot2 for visualization",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:41:22.226844+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/raw-file-data-extraction-via-api/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We use a complete LC-MS run recorded on a Q Exactive HF Orbitrap by parallel reaction monitoring (PRM)... Individual scans or scan collections (sets) can be read by the function read Spectrum() which returns a rawrr Spectrum object or rawrr Spectrum Set... The respective function is called read File Header() and returns a simple R object of type list",
      "asbval:note": "Q Exactive HF explicitly mentioned; readSpectrum, readChromatogram, readFileHeader all demonstrated in use cases.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "raw-file-data-extraction-via-api",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have a Thermo Fisher Scientific .raw file (e.g., Q Exactive HF, Orbitrap) and need to extract specific spectral scans, chromatographic traces, scan-level metadata, or file-level headers programmatically",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:41:22.226844+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/raw-file-data-extraction-via-api/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "By changing the scan filter, one can easily switch between generating precursor traces and fragment ion traces... When subsetting it for our scan type of interest it becomes clear that the example data was recorded using parallel reaction monitoring (PRM) since the parent ion 487.2567 was isolated in regularly spaced intervals for fragment ion recording. The delta between consecutive scans is always 22 scans (one PRM cycle)",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates scan filtering and inter-scan delta computation (22-scan PRM cycle), but does not explicitly show filtering by acquisition type string like 'FTMS + c NSI Full ms2'. The capability is implied but not explicitly demonstrated in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "raw-file-data-extraction-via-api",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This is particularly valuable when you need to filter scans by acquisition type (e.g., 'FTMS + c NSI Full ms2') or compute inter-scan deltas to verify instrument method fidelity.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:41:22.226844+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/raw-file-data-extraction-via-api/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "However, analyzing Orbitrap data in R has so far only been possible after raw data conversion to exchange formats like mz(X)ML. Unfortunately, conversion is accompanied by a loss of Orbitrap-specific information... Libraries that support working with the spectral data in R also exist, for instance, the Bioconductor package MSnbase. However, they require conversion of raw data to exchange formats like mzML, which is primarily supported by the ProteoWizard project and its software tool MSconvert.",
      "asbval:note": "ProteoWizard and MSconvert mentioned as alternatives for non-.raw formats. OpenMS and pyteomics mentioned earlier in the same passage as alternative software libraries.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "raw-file-data-extraction-via-api",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input file is not in Thermo Fisher Scientific .raw format (e.g., mzML, mzXML, NetCDF)\u2014use ProteoWizard, pyteomics, or OpenMS instead",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:41:22.226844+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-extraction-from-raw-spectra/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "By applying linear regression, one can convert observed peptide retention times (RTs) into dimensionless scores termed iRT values and vice versa. This can be used for retention time calibration/prediction. In addition, fitted iRT regression models provide highly valuable information about LC-MS run performance. This example shows how easy it is to perform iRT regression in R by just using the raw measurement data, our package rawrr, and well-known base R functions supporting linear modeling.",
      "asbval:note": "Passage directly describes iRT regression workflow using rawrr to extract RTs and fit linear models for validation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-extraction-from-raw-spectra",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Extract and validate retention time measurements from Thermo Fisher Scientific Orbitrap raw files by reading chromatographic data, fitting intensity traces to identify apex retention times, and evaluating linearity through regression modeling.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:41:44.336298+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-extraction-from-raw-spectra/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our novel package rawrr now provides complete, OS-independent access to all spectral data logged in Thermo Fisher Scientific raw files... This manuscript presents a first package version/release and showcases its usage for bottom-up proteomics data analysis with a focus on Orbitrap data.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states rawrr provides access to Thermo .raw files for bottom-up proteomics.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-extraction-from-raw-spectra",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "bridges proprietary binary .raw file formats to quantitative RT calibration and quality control in bottom-up proteomics",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:41:44.336298+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-extraction-from-raw-spectra/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Table 1. List of rawrr Package Functions Connected to Reading Functionality: read File Header() Reads meta information from a raw file header list; read Spectrum() Reads spectral data from a raw file rawrr Spectrum(Set); read Chromatogram() Reads chromatographic data from a raw file rawrr Chromatogram(Set)",
      "asbval:note": "Function names in paper use camelCase (readFileHeader, readChromatogram, readSpectrum) matching card's claim (case-insensitive). All three functions confirmed present.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-jproteome-0c00866",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-extraction-from-raw-spectra",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "rawrr: R package providing direct read access to Thermo .raw file binary data; supplies readFileHeader(), readChromatogram(), and readSpectrum() functions for metadata and intensity trace extraction",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
